The Arabia-Africa-Uruguay Street

We arrived at the turn where female workers and guards started quarreling with one another. Soon the contest would spread to all the workers. The man confirmed our suspicions that all had something to gain or lose: the city’s authorities and the planners of the project believed they could decrease the pressure on the main arteries of the city by relocating the booths to the side streets; merchants believed that by moving the booths they would be able to control some of their fellow merchants and this would allow them to raise prices; and finally, shouldn’t all the merchants be moved in order to enhance their image? Somalis simply plunged into a scrum, it is their honorable warrior culture.

I ought to mention something about our driver. It is important to remember that I had to report on the amount of money that his employer paid to the occupier for using the road just as I would have to report on the ‘ball lands’ – beginning from a certain point and ending in another.

A Somaliland man was banned from talking about religion by the police – and then killed for his misdeeds.

(Crowds outside Mr Hussein’s husiness premises in Afgoye after he was struck dead)
